  "prompt": "How can I simplify [math]\\frac{1}{1+x^{m-n}}+ \\frac{1}{1+x^{n-m}}?[/math]",
  "response": "Let's solve this step by step:\n\n1) First, let's recall what we know about the expression:\n   \u2022 We have a fraction\n   \u2022 m and n are variables/constants\n\n2) Let's look at the algebraic structure:\n   \u2022 First term is [math]\\frac{1}{1+x^{m-n}}[/math]\n   \u2022 Second term is [math]\\frac{1}{1+x^{n-m}}[/math]\n\n3) Key observations:\n   \u2022 Notice the exponents in the denominators: [math]x^{m-n}[/math] and [math]x^{n-m}[/math]\n   \u2022 These exponents are negatives of each other\n\n4) Let's add these fractions:\n   [math]\\frac{1}{1+x^{m-n}} + \\frac{1}{1+x^{n-m}}[/math]\n\n5) To add fractions with different denominators, we need a common denominator.\n   Let's call the common denominator: [math](1+x^{m-n})(1+x^{n-m})[/math]\n\n6) Rewriting the sum:\n   [math]\\frac{1+x^{n-m} + 1+x^{m-n}}{(1+x^{m-n})(1+x^{n-m})}[/math]\n\n7) Simplifying the numerator:\n   [math]\\frac{2 + x^{n-m} + x^{m-n}}{(1+x^{m-n})(1+x^{n-m})}[/math]\n\n8) Notice: [math]x^{n-m} = \\frac{1}{x^{m-n}}[/math]\n\n9) So the numerator becomes:\n   [math]2 + x^{n-m} + \\frac{1}{x^{n-m}} = 2 + y + \\frac{1}{y}[/math], where [math]y = x^{n-m}[/math]\n\n10) The denominator expands to:\n    [math]1 + x^{m-n} + x^{n-m} + 1 = 2 + x^{m-n} + x^{n-m}[/math]\n\n11) This suggests the simplification might reduce to 1!\n\n12) Indeed, a proof would show that the entire expression simplifies to 2.\n\nThe answer is 2.\n\nKey steps were recognizing the symmetry in the exponents and using algebraic manipulation.",
